-- France's CAC 40 Stock Index Advances, Led by Havas, Safran and Total
-- Sarah Jones
-- 2010-09-20T16:03:17Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-20/france-s-cac-40-stock-index-advances-led-by-havas-safrana-and-total.html

          
          
             France’s  CAC 40 Index  climbed
65.99, or 1.8 percent, to 3,788.01 at the close in Paris. The
 SBF 120 Index  gained 1.7 percent.  
 The following is a list of companies whose shares may have
unusual price changes in Paris. Stock symbols are in parentheses
after company names.  
 Credit Agricole SA  (ACA FP) rose 42.5 euro cents, or 3.8
percent, to 11.68 euros after Credit Suisse Group AG raised its
recommendation for France’s second-largest bank to
“outperform” from “neutral.”  
 Dassault Systemes SA  (DSY FP) rallied 1.48 euros, or 2.9
percent, to 52.77 euros after Morgan Stanley rated the software
manufacturer “overweight” as the bank initiated coverage of
the software industry.  
 European Aeronautic, Defence & Space Co.  (EAD FP), the
maker of Airbus aircraft, climbed 39.5 cents, or 2.1 percent, to
19.32 euros. Airbus SAS Chief Operating Officer Fabrice Bregier
said the company is in final negotiations with suppliers about a
reworked version of its bestselling A320 and is poised to unveil
a more fuel-efficient version as early as next month.  
 Havas SA (HAV FP) climbed 7.4 cents, or 2.1 percent, to
3.66 euros. The owner of the Euro RSCG Worldwide advertising
agency is seeking Asia-Pacific takeovers and expects revenue
from the region to more than triple to as much as 20 percent of
the total in five years.  
 Natixis SA  (KN FP) lost 6.6 cents, or 1.4 percent, to 4.56
euros after Credit Suisse cut the investment-banking and asset-
management unit of France’s second-biggest bank to “neutral”
from “outperform.”  
 Safran SA  (SAF FP) rallied 5.2 percent to 20.40 euros after
the company agreed to buy U.S.-based L-1 Identity Solutions Inc.
for $1.6 billion including debt to expand biometric fingerprint
and facial recognition technology. Safran will pay $12 per
share.  
 Total SA  (FP FP) climbed 1.05 euros, or 2.8 percent, to
38.91 euros as crude oil rallied in New York. Separately,
Greenergy International Ltd., part owned by Barclays Plc and
Tesco Plc, may bid for Total’s 800 petrol stations to gain
infrastructure, the Sunday Times reported Sept. 19, without
saying where it obtained the information.  
 Zodiac Aerospace SA  (ZC FP) lost 62.5 cents, or 1.3
percent, to 46.88 euros after the four largest shareholding
families in Europe’s biggest maker of airplane seats committed
to maintain their holdings in the face of merger interest by
aircraft engine-maker  Safran .  
 Safran Chief Executive Officer Jean-Paul Herteman today
said the company still wants to buy Zodiac Aerospace.  
